RBS suspends two forex traders
The Royal Bank of Scotland has suspended two traders from its foreign exchange department, two people familiar with the matter said, another indication that global investigations by regulators into suspected manipulation of the currency market are progressing at a rapid pace.
Some of the world's largest banks, including UBS Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed they are cooperating with regulators in investigations into the world's largest financial market, which transacts $5.3 trillion each day.
The two traders will be the first employees of RBS to be suspended as the investigation into what appears to be a repeat of the Libor interbank credit manipulation scandal progresses.
The bank declined to comment on the suspension, confirming that it had received a request for information from regulators this month.
Two weeks ago, the bank had said, "Our investigation in this matter is ongoing, and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and other regulators." "
Last month, people familiar with the matter said RBS had sent records of emails and instant messages sent to and received from former traders to the UK regulator, the Financial Conduct Authority.
Richard Usher left RBS in 2010 and is believed to have been relieved from his current position as European head of forex spot trading at JP Morgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, head of European spot trading at Citi, went on leave last week, while the former senior currency trader at Barclays and UBS was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
None of these traders have been accused of any wrongdoing.
People familiar with the matter said that Mr. Usher's instant messaging group includes bankers from Barclays and Citigroup.
UBS said it has taken action against some of its employees this week after the Swiss regulator, Finma, reported that it was investigating suspected manipulation of the foreign exchange market in several Swiss banks.
At least six authorities globally – the European Commission, Finma, Switzerland's competition authority Vico, the FCA, the Department of Justice in the US, and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority – are investigating allegations of collusion against bankers to facilitate their optimal volatility in the currency market.
HSBC, Citigroup, JP Morgan, and Credit Suisse have also conducted internal investigations, or received requests for information from regulators, people familiar with the matter said.
Banks are closely examining instant messages and emails equivalent to several years in search of clues to any wrongdoing.
The news about the investigation has caused panic among traders in the sector, who have been among the top profit-makers in the trading unit of investment banks for the past several years, but are facing a challenge this year as low volatility in currencies has reduced opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers tried to hush up the matter by saying that it is an impossible scene to manipulate a very large and highly liquid forex exchange, but senior traders say this is not necessarily true.
The senior trader said that despite the huge volume of forex buying and selling, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and the increasing use of their own platforms by banks means that "you can start influencing the market at a slightly lower ticket price." "
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse announced the departure of the trader from its Exchange Traded Funds Desk in London this week, which had posted a loss of about $6 million at the end of last year.
The Bank immediately notified the relevant authorities and is cooperating with its regulators.
Credit Suisse said that "we believe that the trader acted alone, and has been controlled." "
