The Civil Aviation Safety Authority also said it was considering the announcement, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electrical equipment at critical stages of flight are still in effect in Australia.
"At present, CASA does not have any specific regulation governing the use of electrical equipment in aircraft," the authority said, adding, "The issue is subject to regulations, according to which airlines have to ensure that safety arrangements are always fully in place, and passengers have to comply with safety instructions given by crew members." "
Virgin, which is already in talks with CASA about expanding the use of its in-flight Wi-Fi entertainment system, is ready to comply with this change, but asked for further action on the regulator's directive.
"We would welcome the review by CASA in terms of allowing the use of electrical equipment, as we really feel that it will provide a better experience to customers, as we now have (wireless in-flight entertainment) in our planes," the spokesperson said.
