Previous research has shown that happy dogs move their tails more on the right side (from the dog's point of view), while restless dogs move their tails more mainly on the left.
But now scientists say companion dogs can recognize this subtle distinction of the tail and react to it.
The study was published in the journal Current Biology.
Professor Georgia Vellertigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, explained: "It is well known in humans that the left and right sides of the brain are involved differently in the stimulus that generates positive or negative emotions. "
Here we have tried to see it in other species as well.
They reported that in dogs, just like humans, the right side of the brain was responsible for left-hand movements and opposite order, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to unilateral nostrils by other dogs, the researchers tracked animals watching other dogs' movies.
They measured the heartbeats of pet dogs and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't take us long to understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
Pro. Vellartigra explained: "We introduced the dogs to movies of dogs – in a realistic version or in the photograph to deal with other confusing issues, and we could see the movement of the tail and render the tail more left or right. "
When the animals saw an emotionless dog moving its tail to the right (from the sight of the dog), they were completely relaxed.
But when he saw the tail changing direction mainly to the left (again from the dog's point of view), his heartbeat increased and he looked restless.
Pro. According to Vellartigara, he does not think the dogs were intentionally communicating with each other through these movements.
Instead, they think dogs have learned from their own experience what movements they should be concerned about and what they shouldn't.
He said: "If you've met other dogs several times, and if they move their tails consistently to one side it's related to more friendly behavior, and the right side presents less friendly behavior, you react based on the same experience." "
The findings could provide owners, veterinarians and trainers with a better understanding of animal emotions, the researchers said.
"This is not the first study to examine whether the left or right side is important for dogs," said John Bradshaw, a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol's School of Veterinary Sciences.
Last year, a team at the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they see an aggressive dog and turn their head to the right when they see a happy dog.
