New anti-nicotine vaccine may end smoking pleasure
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that can end the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to keep mice safe from nicotine addiction for the rest of their lives.
Further testing is needed before human trials can begin, which could take several years, but Ronald Crystal, a professor at Weill Cornell Medical College in New York, said the initial signs were positive.
"We are very hopeful that this type of vaccine strategy may eventually help the millions of smokers who have attempted to quit smoking using all the methods that are on the market today, but they found that their addiction to nicotine is far more powerful than these current methods," Cornell said. "
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus designed to deliver genetic information aimed at creating anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cell, which then begins to form a steady stream of antibodies.
Antibodies detect any nicotine molecules in the blood, and by neutralizing them before they reach the brain, they prevent nicotine cravings from rising inside the smoker.
In the trial, the vaccinated mice that were later given nicotine continued to perform their normal activities.
But the rat that wasn't given the vaccine "felt good," the researchers said, adding that it was a sign that nicotine had reached its brain.
The experiment was described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Earlier tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The dose had to be given at regular intervals so that the level of antibodies was maintained, but it proved to be expensive and impractical.
But the price of the new vaccine is expected to be very high, because the liver will make the cell a factory of antibodies.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine is completely safe, it can be given to children before the temptation to try cigarettes, so that they can be protected from nicotine addiction.
But it will probably be used by smokers to quit smoking.
"They will find that if they start smoking again, they won't get any pleasure from smoking because of the nicotine vaccine, which can help them quit the habit," he said.
British scientists described the results as interesting, but warned of the need for much more research.
